WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.317 --> 00:00:05.900
MALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon everyone.

00:00:05.900 --> 00:00:08.108
Welcome to another outstanding
Talks at Google event.

00:00:08.108 --> 00:00:10.095
And today for our
Food Google program,

00:00:10.095 --> 00:00:12.860
we're very thrilled
to welcome back

00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:15.230
Jody Eddy and Gunnar
Karl Gislason.

00:00:15.230 --> 00:00:17.230
They will be
speaking to us today

00:00:17.230 --> 00:00:18.850
about their latest
cookbook, which

00:00:18.850 --> 00:00:22.500
is called "North: The New
Nordic Cuisine of Iceland".

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:25.180
And some of us in the audience,
I know myself personally,

00:00:25.180 --> 00:00:27.680
have traveled in the
beautiful country,

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:32.220
seen the food that was there,
the fish and everything.

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:34.010
And really with
what the book does

00:00:34.010 --> 00:00:37.380
is not only talk about Gunnar's
restaurant-- which is Dill,

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:41.330
and very well known, one of
the top Nordic restaurants

00:00:41.330 --> 00:00:45.280
in Iceland and a continuation
of the new Nordic cuisine

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:47.020
tradition from Rene Redzepi.

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:49.330
But the book also
goes into background

00:00:49.330 --> 00:00:51.890
about the various producers
throughout the country.

00:00:51.890 --> 00:00:58.710
So from the folks that provide
the salt, to the goat's milk,

00:00:58.710 --> 00:01:00.710
to the people that
are harvesting bird

00:01:00.710 --> 00:01:02.530
eggs off the coast
of Iceland, there's

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:04.260
a story for each one involved.

00:01:04.260 --> 00:01:07.210
And so we will have some
time for Q&amp;A at the end,

00:01:07.210 --> 00:01:09.000
so I encourage you to
check the book out.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.750
We are sampling some
Icelandic cuisine as well.

00:01:11.750 --> 00:01:14.120
Hop on down to the beautiful
country if you get a chance

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:17.330
and please join me in welcoming
Gunnar and Jody to Google.

00:01:17.330 --> 00:01:19.805
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:24.480
JODY EDDY: So thank you
so much for coming today.

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:26.390
And I thought it
would just start out

00:01:26.390 --> 00:01:28.510
by talking a little
bit about my history

00:01:28.510 --> 00:01:34.150
with Gunnar where we met and I
met him maybe five years ago.

00:01:34.150 --> 00:01:38.310
It was right when the economic
collapse of Iceland's economy

00:01:38.310 --> 00:01:40.915
had just happened
and I was shooting--

00:01:40.915 --> 00:01:43.260
I was an editor at
a culinary magazine

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:46.200
and I was most excited
to meet with Gunnar

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:48.000
of all the chefs
I met in Iceland.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.070
And when I got there,
to the restaurant,

00:01:50.070 --> 00:01:52.390
they said that he wasn't there.

00:01:52.390 --> 00:01:55.300
And I was really disappointed,
I had to leave the next day.

00:01:55.300 --> 00:02:01.132
But then he walked into Dill
carrying a basket of angelica

00:02:01.132 --> 00:02:02.840
that he had just been
collecting outside,

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:04.610
and so he had been there.

00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:07.530
And we just stayed in
touch throughout the years,

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:11.380
and then a variety of
projects together and.

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:14.610
He was in my last book on
restaurant staff meals.

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:19.100
And when we finished
that up, I didn't really

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:20.660
have a project in
the works with him.

00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:23.550
And we had a conversation
that night at the photo shoot

00:02:23.550 --> 00:02:26.060
and talked about how we
should do something together,

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:30.180
profiling the traditional
food producers of Iceland

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:32.440
because they're so
important to Gunnar.

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:35.300
Can you talk a little bit about
why they mean so much to you?

00:02:35.780 --> 00:02:37.280
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Well the thing

00:02:37.280 --> 00:02:40.510
is when I first opened
up the restaurant,

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:42.630
it was five and half years ago.

00:02:44.710 --> 00:02:47.060
It started up us
being-- like, it

00:02:47.060 --> 00:02:49.065
was supposed be, like
a Nordic restaurant.

00:02:49.065 --> 00:02:51.359
And I wanted to try
to collect ingredients

00:02:51.359 --> 00:02:52.900
from all around the
Nordic countries.

00:02:54.090 --> 00:02:57.360
The collapse came and
pretty much everything

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:02.580
that I was going to import was
going up in prices like crazy.

00:03:03.710 --> 00:03:08.890
So we somehow started
going another way.

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:14.410
We started with
the usual suspects

00:03:14.410 --> 00:03:17.060
and then went from there
trying to find something more,

00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:21.070
trying to find something
new-- in my case,

00:03:21.070 --> 00:03:23.990
maybe trying to find
something old, actually.

00:03:23.990 --> 00:03:29.210
And very quickly I
found this passion

00:03:29.210 --> 00:03:32.300
for finding those
producers that are

00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:36.380
making their things the old way.

00:03:36.380 --> 00:03:39.480
And so I was trying
to find them.

00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:43.760
And even harder
was to find out how

00:03:43.760 --> 00:03:47.230
I could take those ingredients
and make something,

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:51.140
like new out of it, something
new that would be like-- that

00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:54.510
would fit perfectly into
a fine dining restaurant.

00:03:54.510 --> 00:03:58.480
And for some things
it was really easy

00:03:58.480 --> 00:03:59.690
and came very natural.

00:03:59.690 --> 00:04:03.995
For other things, it was
like months of headache.

00:04:05.180 --> 00:04:05.770
But--

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:06.770
JODY EDDY: Why was that?

00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:08.050
Why was it a challenge?

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:13.180
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: I mean
to take a little dried wolffish

00:04:13.180 --> 00:04:17.070
and make something really
enjoyable out of it.

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:20.300
Not that I'm saying
it's bad like it is,

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:24.597
but it's more like you will
have to do something with it

00:04:24.597 --> 00:04:25.680
so it fits the restaurant.

00:04:27.450 --> 00:04:28.940
Usually we just eat it.

00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:33.055
Like at home, we just tear it
down, cover it with butter,

00:04:33.055 --> 00:04:33.930
and eat it like that.

00:04:34.962 --> 00:04:37.170
But obviously I had to do
something a little bit more

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:39.820
interesting so I could
serve it at the restaurant.

00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:42.300
And especially, the
dried fish actually

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:44.680
was kind of a headache.

00:04:44.680 --> 00:04:47.070
But now I have a
couple of things

00:04:47.070 --> 00:04:49.910
that I like doing with it.

00:04:49.910 --> 00:04:51.850
JODY EDDY: Hardfiskur,
what he's referencing,

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:53.430
is that a dried wolffish.

00:04:53.430 --> 00:04:56.970
It's dried in drying
houses on the ocean.

00:04:56.970 --> 00:04:59.980
And it's certainly
a tradition that

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:01.920
is disappearing
in Iceland, and I

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:06.520
think that's what inspires
me most about Gunnar,

00:05:06.520 --> 00:05:09.850
is that he is taking these
traditional ingredients

00:05:09.850 --> 00:05:13.120
that even maybe Icelanders
aren't appreciating anymore

00:05:13.120 --> 00:05:15.410
and he's transforming
them into something

00:05:15.410 --> 00:05:20.250
beautiful and contemporary, but
still pays homage to the past.

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:23.900
And his connections
to his producers,

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:28.280
I've so often seen
that he's really

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:30.400
keeping the traditional
alive in some cases,

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:35.070
and in some cases
actually transforming

00:05:35.070 --> 00:05:38.040
a tradition, and also
just making Icelanders

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:40.735
appreciate what they have.

00:05:40.735 --> 00:05:42.130
GUNNAR KARL
GISLASON: Yes, right.

00:05:42.130 --> 00:05:46.480
It's like when I started
researching those things

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:49.240
and finding all those
people at the same time,

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:52.320
I was finding out that
they were really, really

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:53.670
slowly fading away.

00:05:54.981 --> 00:05:56.730
And all the companies,
they were coming up

00:05:56.730 --> 00:06:01.630
with both easier and cheaper--
and most of all, faster-- ways

00:06:01.630 --> 00:06:02.950
to do their things.

00:06:02.950 --> 00:06:05.320
Like for example
with the dried fish,

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:07.940
it's mostly dried now
in some kind of ovens.

00:06:09.300 --> 00:06:12.210
Which is fine, there's
nothing wrong with it per se.

00:06:13.370 --> 00:06:16.402
But it's just not the
same as other one.

00:06:16.402 --> 00:06:19.680
The other one obviously
is like really

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:23.210
packed of flavors from the
sea after hanging there.

00:06:24.290 --> 00:06:28.310
So the thing is that you have to
find the place for your house,

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:29.960
and you should find
the place where

00:06:29.960 --> 00:06:33.170
it's as windy as it
can be, pretty much.

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:35.270
And then it's only dried
during the wintertime

00:06:35.270 --> 00:06:37.560
because the temperature
has to be below zero.

00:06:38.860 --> 00:06:42.250
And it takes one month,
up to two months,

00:06:42.250 --> 00:06:45.070
depending on everything.

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:49.500
And obviously the fish will
be really packed with flavors.

00:06:51.510 --> 00:06:54.390
And there are many other
assembles-- for an example,

00:06:54.390 --> 00:07:01.060
with a salted cod-- that
is like, back in the days,

00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:04.857
it takes almost like up
to a year to make it.

00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:11.760
But nowadays it's more
starting to be new ways,

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:14.650
injecting saltwater and
et cetera, et cetera.

00:07:14.650 --> 00:07:17.150
But still we are
so lucky to have

00:07:17.150 --> 00:07:19.960
a couple that are still
doing it the old way.

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:22.454
And obviously we buy theirs.

00:07:22.454 --> 00:07:23.370
JODY EDDY: Absolutely.

00:07:23.370 --> 00:07:27.550
And can you talk a little bit--
because I think there's maybe

00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:31.350
a bit of misconception about
what New Nordic cuisine is all

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:35.650
about and what Nordic cuisine--
contemporary Nordic cuisine--

00:07:35.650 --> 00:07:36.240
is about?

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:38.210
And maybe talk a
little bit about what

00:07:38.210 --> 00:07:41.620
the manifesto for the new
Nordic kitchen was and--?

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:48.220
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah,
well it's like-- I don't know.

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:50.390
It's actually quite
a long time ago

00:07:50.390 --> 00:07:52.540
since the manifesto was made.

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:55.790
It was actually a couple of
chefs from the Nordic countries

00:07:55.790 --> 00:07:59.650
that actually all got together
and made this little manifesto

00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:02.210
of things that
should be something

00:08:02.210 --> 00:08:04.600
that would embrace
our countries.

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:06.390
The whole idea--
the first idea, I

00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:10.460
guess-- was to try to
make a kitchen that

00:08:10.460 --> 00:08:12.750
could be well-known,
like worldwide.

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:18.520
And I guess people like, they
saw that it could be a problem

00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:23.345
to make like one country to
make a Norwegian kitchen,

00:08:23.345 --> 00:08:25.000
or a Danish kitchen
for that matter,

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.020
and make it like really, really
big so it could get like longer

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:31.910
and wider like the Italian
kitchen or the French kitchen,

00:08:31.910 --> 00:08:33.390
et cetera.

00:08:33.390 --> 00:08:35.070
So they decided
somehow-- and I think

00:08:35.070 --> 00:08:39.159
that was one of the reasons that
it would be good to take them

00:08:39.159 --> 00:08:42.740
all together,
somehow like trying

00:08:42.740 --> 00:08:46.850
to take the Nordic countries
and everybody like work together

00:08:46.850 --> 00:08:51.210
and try to embrace
each other and that we

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:56.200
could get that Nordic
kitchen on the map.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:09:00.760
And it happened
so fast and so big

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:03.060
that I think nobody believed it.

00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:10.830
And now it's, I don't know, it's
like somehow maybe those words,

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:14.860
like the Nordic
kitchen, are-- for me,

00:09:14.860 --> 00:09:17.190
at least-- some people
use it to describe

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:19.290
a certain type of food.

00:09:19.290 --> 00:09:22.380
But for me, it's more
like a Nordic kitchen

00:09:22.380 --> 00:09:26.090
would be like a
restaurant that are using

00:09:26.090 --> 00:09:28.270
those ingredients that
are close to them.

00:09:32.050 --> 00:09:35.640
But they could be
really different

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:37.880
when it comes to
how to make the food

00:09:37.880 --> 00:09:41.950
or how to plate it or
serve it for that matter.

00:09:41.950 --> 00:09:45.990
So for me it's like
a very big umbrella

00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:50.840
for a lot of things for a lot
of kitchens, techniques, and et

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:51.444
cetera.

00:09:51.444 --> 00:09:53.110
JODY EDDY: And I think
one of the things

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:55.130
that we really talk a
lot about in our cookbook

00:09:55.130 --> 00:09:58.010
is that you can take
these techniques,

00:09:58.010 --> 00:10:01.680
or you can take this
philosophy and really apply it

00:10:01.680 --> 00:10:04.210
anywhere in the world,
and incorporate it.

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:09.920
They talk so much about a sense
of place in Nordic countries

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:12.370
and associated with
the term New Nordic.

00:10:12.370 --> 00:10:15.230
And it really does mean that,
you know-- look outside.

00:10:15.230 --> 00:10:18.900
If there's something in the
cookbook that you can't source,

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:22.720
just find out what's in your
own backyard and use that.

00:10:22.720 --> 00:10:26.010
And I think that's really
the philosophy of what

00:10:26.010 --> 00:10:30.051
Nordic cuisine is about, as
opposed to specific techniques

00:10:30.051 --> 00:10:30.675
or ingredients.

00:10:31.244 --> 00:10:33.410
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: You
just go into your backyard

00:10:33.410 --> 00:10:36.254
and find whatever
you have and use it.

00:10:36.254 --> 00:10:36.920
JODY EDDY: Yeah.

00:10:36.920 --> 00:10:38.940
Can you talk a little
bit more about--?

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:39.580
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Just make sure not

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:40.830
to eat something poison.

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:41.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:41.330 --> 00:10:42.121
JODY EDDY: Exactly.

00:10:42.121 --> 00:10:45.440
Can you talk a little bit
more about the techniques--

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:47.780
like the specific
techniques-- in Iceland

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:49.210
that are really
unique to Iceland?

00:10:50.980 --> 00:10:53.105
Cooking techniques,
maybe your hay smoking

00:10:53.105 --> 00:10:57.062
and smoking with
manure and those.

00:10:58.517 --> 00:11:00.350
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Yeah, probably now you

00:11:00.350 --> 00:11:01.600
want to hear about the manure.

00:11:01.600 --> 00:11:04.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:04.110 --> 00:11:08.020
It's actually like-- that's
one of the old traditions

00:11:08.020 --> 00:11:13.180
as well, probably since
the time of Vikings.

00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:17.470
It's something that was
a technique that-- so,

00:11:17.470 --> 00:11:19.580
during the winter
time, the sheeps

00:11:19.580 --> 00:11:21.960
would be inside the houses.

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:23.560
They would all,
obviously, they would

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:26.130
do number one and
two on the floor

00:11:26.130 --> 00:11:27.695
and have some hay in between.

00:11:27.695 --> 00:11:29.320
And they'd walk on
it the whole winter.

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:32.419
So it's thick like this in
the beginning of the summer.

00:11:32.419 --> 00:11:34.210
In the beginning of
the summer, the sheeps,

00:11:34.210 --> 00:11:36.685
they just go up to the
mountains and live really

00:11:36.685 --> 00:11:39.572
freely there all summer.

00:11:39.572 --> 00:11:41.030
The farmers on the
other hand, they

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:44.826
would go and cut it into layers,
take it outside, and dry it.

00:11:44.826 --> 00:11:46.450
And it's actually
it's like-- I thought

00:11:46.450 --> 00:11:48.300
it was like a really
basic technique,

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:50.980
but it's really kind
of complicated to find

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:57.700
the exact right manure to use.

00:11:57.700 --> 00:12:01.420
Because it cannot be too
dry, it cannot be too wet.

00:12:01.420 --> 00:12:04.640
If it's too dry, it will
just go up in flames.

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:08.010
If it's too wet, it
obviously won't burn.

00:12:08.010 --> 00:12:12.440
So it's a kind of
complicated technique.

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:15.657
And obviously it
takes a long time,

00:12:15.657 --> 00:12:17.240
and obviously you
have to have sheeps.

00:12:18.390 --> 00:12:23.330
But it's probably like
something that-- I mean,

00:12:23.330 --> 00:12:25.460
they didn't start doing
it because they really

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:27.740
just love their shit so much.

00:12:27.740 --> 00:12:30.760
But it's probably
more because they

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:32.520
didn't have anything
else to burn.

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:36.170
So there were a serious, serious
lack of trees in Iceland.

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:41.840
And it actually went so
far that at a certain time

00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:46.180
they started to try to protect
those few trees that we

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:46.780
had left.

00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:50.430
So obviously people have
to find something else

00:12:50.430 --> 00:12:53.650
to dry and burn or
smoke with, or whatever.

00:12:53.650 --> 00:12:56.807
So this was one of the things
that they came up with.

00:12:56.807 --> 00:12:58.890
JODY EDDY: And I think
that's certainly something,

00:12:58.890 --> 00:13:02.050
after traveling in
Iceland for many years,

00:13:02.050 --> 00:13:08.880
that I see over and over again
is that they-- often, it's

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:11.150
a matter of survival, really.

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:14.820
And so you really have to
be clever and figure out

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:16.200
how to use what you have.

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:21.860
We'll talk a little bit later
about the geothermal salt

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:27.010
maker who makes salt using
geothermal heat, the rye bread

00:13:27.010 --> 00:13:30.172
producer who uses, instead of
wood, using geothermal heat

00:13:30.172 --> 00:13:32.255
from the ground in baking
the bread in the ground.

00:13:34.600 --> 00:13:37.820
There's just so many different
ingredients and techniques

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:45.030
that I think really reflect
that tradition of not having

00:13:45.030 --> 00:13:48.230
anything and just
having to be clever.

00:13:49.470 --> 00:13:54.220
Yeah, and can you just
talk a little bit more

00:13:54.220 --> 00:14:02.700
about the geothermal
energy and the heat,

00:14:02.700 --> 00:14:07.410
and also about how Iceland
is such a pristine country?

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:11.030
They've tried to market
Iceland as one of the only 100%

00:14:11.030 --> 00:14:13.680
sustainable nations
because of the fact

00:14:13.680 --> 00:14:16.845
that you don't have chemicals,
the animals are free range,

00:14:16.845 --> 00:14:17.970
they don't use antibiotics.

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:22.170
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Most of it, at least.

00:14:25.310 --> 00:14:30.750
We try to use that heat from
the ground for some good things,

00:14:30.750 --> 00:14:32.030
definitely.

00:14:32.030 --> 00:14:34.400
But obviously it can sometimes
be a little bit hard,

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:36.860
because, I think,
I can't use it,

00:14:36.860 --> 00:14:40.870
because I would have to drive
pretty far away to find one.

00:14:40.870 --> 00:14:45.420
But on those areas where they
have that geothermal heat,

00:14:45.420 --> 00:14:47.460
it is used quite a lot.

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:50.000
I think we can use it even more.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:53.295
But for an example, we
have that salt producer.

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:56.710
And they're-- it's
somehow it's like I really

00:14:56.710 --> 00:14:58.876
don't-- it's really only
like a couple of years old,

00:14:58.876 --> 00:14:59.430
that company.

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:04.700
And now there are two
companies making high-end salt

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:06.080
in Iceland.

00:15:06.080 --> 00:15:08.210
But for me it's
just really strange

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:11.500
that we haven't been
doing this like always,

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:12.510
because it's so simple.

00:15:12.510 --> 00:15:15.410
The only thing they do is
they pump some seawater up

00:15:15.410 --> 00:15:17.780
from the sea and
up in some tanks,

00:15:17.780 --> 00:15:19.520
and they dry it over
geothermal heat.

00:15:20.415 --> 00:15:21.290
JODY EDDY: That's it.

00:15:21.290 --> 00:15:24.070
And it's the best
finishing salt and salt

00:15:24.070 --> 00:15:25.925
that I've truly ever eaten.

00:15:25.925 --> 00:15:27.550
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
It's really good.

00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:32.880
But the same with the heat,
obviously like on those places

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:35.430
where there is a lot
of heat in the ground,

00:15:35.430 --> 00:15:41.311
people will use it to cook
with, like to bake the bread,

00:15:41.311 --> 00:15:41.810
for example.

00:15:42.930 --> 00:15:45.505
And obviously we use
it for our greenhouses.

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:50.620
So it's like-- I mean,
greenhouses in general

00:15:50.620 --> 00:15:54.030
may be quite often
looked down at.

00:15:54.030 --> 00:15:57.350
But I think it
could be something

00:15:57.350 --> 00:16:02.490
that we could be proud of in
Iceland because of that heat

00:16:02.490 --> 00:16:03.950
from the ground
that has been used,

00:16:03.950 --> 00:16:08.000
and how green our
electricity is.

00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:11.750
JODY EDDY: And also--
here's a picture.

00:16:11.750 --> 00:16:13.310
What you're seeing
there is whale.

00:16:14.630 --> 00:16:18.340
And I thought we could talk
a little bit about some

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:23.310
of the products that they use in
Iceland, because so often it's

00:16:23.310 --> 00:16:26.290
all they have, and I think
it can be very controversial.

00:16:26.290 --> 00:16:31.560
But I also think it speaks
to using what's around you.

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:35.590
And if you can talk a little
bit more about things maybe

00:16:35.590 --> 00:16:39.190
they would call taboo,
horse meat and whale and--?

00:16:39.912 --> 00:16:41.370
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Yeah, I mean,

00:16:41.370 --> 00:16:44.720
it's like-- definitely,
back in the days, people,

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:46.040
they had to survive.

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:50.720
And they were not going to have
some big issues about if it

00:16:50.720 --> 00:16:52.700
was a whale or something else.

00:16:52.700 --> 00:16:54.100
If they could cook
it and eat it,

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:55.391
they would probably just do it.

00:16:56.800 --> 00:16:59.580
Now, it's like whale--
there's not really

00:16:59.580 --> 00:17:04.385
many people in Iceland who are
eating it, not many at all.

00:17:04.385 --> 00:17:06.760
I'm actually pretty sure it's
like most of the whale sold

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:08.364
in Iceland is sold to tourists.

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:14.589
But there are some more
things like, for an example,

00:17:14.589 --> 00:17:18.740
horses, which are
eaten all year round.

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:24.880
And I actually had
issues eating horse,

00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:27.530
but it is because I came
from the countryside,

00:17:27.530 --> 00:17:28.540
and we raised horses.

00:17:28.540 --> 00:17:30.840
So it was a little bit
like eating my dog.

00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:32.857
But then again, people
do that as well.

00:17:32.857 --> 00:17:33.940
JODY EDDY: Not in Iceland.

00:17:33.940 --> 00:17:35.648
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Not in Iceland, no.

00:17:36.147 --> 00:17:41.610
But then I decided a couple
of months ago, I was like, OK.

00:17:41.610 --> 00:17:42.800
Let's go.

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:45.950
So obviously, I had eaten
some horses back in day.

00:17:45.950 --> 00:17:49.550
But it's actually really good.

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:54.440
If you find the right producer
and you find the right horse,

00:17:54.440 --> 00:17:57.470
actually it's
really, really nice.

00:17:57.470 --> 00:17:59.610
JODY EDDY: I think one
of the questions I always

00:17:59.610 --> 00:18:03.130
get when people hear
that I'm working

00:18:03.130 --> 00:18:06.360
on an Icelandic cookbook
is, what is the shark like?

00:18:06.360 --> 00:18:09.560
And again, I think it's one
of those tired questions

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:14.610
that, there are some notorious
ingredients in Iceland that

00:18:14.610 --> 00:18:19.120
are very traditional and really,
again, speak to that time

00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:21.040
when food was about survival.

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:22.990
It was about getting
through the winter

00:18:22.990 --> 00:18:25.580
and using preservation
techniques.

00:18:25.580 --> 00:18:28.640
They don't necessarily
appeal to the modern palate,

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:32.960
but I think it's important
that these traditions continue,

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:35.820
because it's really
the legacy of Iceland

00:18:35.820 --> 00:18:38.240
and the legacy of
surviving and perseverance.

00:18:38.240 --> 00:18:39.740
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Yeah, exactly.

00:18:41.030 --> 00:18:43.990
And I mean it's like a good
question about that shark,

00:18:43.990 --> 00:18:47.740
because it's something-- I
mean, I wouldn't go so far

00:18:47.740 --> 00:18:51.170
to say that I really dislike
it, but it's not really pleasant

00:18:51.170 --> 00:18:51.880
at all.

00:18:51.880 --> 00:18:56.150
It smells like
really, really strong.

00:18:56.150 --> 00:18:59.610
But actually after you
start you eating it,

00:18:59.610 --> 00:19:02.690
it smells more than
it actually tastes.

00:19:02.690 --> 00:19:05.110
And a lot of people
actually, it's

00:19:05.110 --> 00:19:08.670
like-- I met a lot
of foodies people

00:19:08.670 --> 00:19:10.625
that are really
into strong cheeses.

00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:14.840
And they actually just
happen to enjoy this a lot,

00:19:14.840 --> 00:19:19.495
because it's like the texture
and everything is actually

00:19:19.495 --> 00:19:20.620
a lot like a strong cheese.

00:19:21.740 --> 00:19:27.520
And it's like again, even though
I don't really love eating it,

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:32.120
it would be a big shame
if it were to die out.

00:19:32.120 --> 00:19:36.120
And the technique, again, is
something that takes months.

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:40.490
Yeah, it would be a shame.

00:19:40.490 --> 00:19:41.156
JODY EDDY: Yeah.

00:19:41.156 --> 00:19:44.600
And we did meet with
a-- so it's a fermented

00:19:44.600 --> 00:19:47.900
or, essentially,
putrefied Shark.

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:51.160
And we met with a--
it's called hakarl--

00:19:51.160 --> 00:19:52.670
with a hakarl producer.

00:19:52.670 --> 00:19:56.890
And talking with him-- he's
in his, I think, 80s now--

00:19:56.890 --> 00:19:59.420
and there isn't
anyone who is going

00:19:59.420 --> 00:20:01.630
to take over what he's doing.

00:20:01.630 --> 00:20:04.350
And so even if this
ingredient isn't something

00:20:04.350 --> 00:20:08.630
that appeals to
everyone, it's really sad

00:20:08.630 --> 00:20:11.170
that it might disappear
when he disappears.

00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:15.420
I have a picture
here of puffins.

00:20:16.700 --> 00:20:20.160
And that's another ingredient
I think in Iceland that it's

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:24.440
a part of Icelandic tradition,
but not necessarily something

00:20:24.440 --> 00:20:26.240
that you would--

00:20:27.122 --> 00:20:29.580
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: It's very
like-- what do you call it?

00:20:29.580 --> 00:20:32.590
It's very like, a local thing.

00:20:32.590 --> 00:20:35.000
So he's not just everywhere.

00:20:36.230 --> 00:20:39.630
But, yeah definitely like
[INAUDIBLE] and Grimsey,

00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:44.310
they will have a lot of it,
[INAUDIBLE] and in the west.

00:20:44.310 --> 00:20:47.540
But now it's
protected, in a way.

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:50.026
I think you're allowed
to go and hunt it,

00:20:50.026 --> 00:20:51.400
but you're not
allowed to sell it

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:55.260
and you're not allowed to
sell it in the restaurants.

00:20:55.260 --> 00:20:58.040
Yeah, but it's a very
big tradition in Iceland

00:20:58.040 --> 00:20:59.010
to eat those.

00:20:59.010 --> 00:21:04.480
And not only those, but to a lot
of birds in their same family,

00:21:04.480 --> 00:21:08.220
and even at a time of
some of their eggs.

00:21:09.540 --> 00:21:12.860
JODY EDDY: And here's a photo
of somebody baking-- I'm sorry,

00:21:12.860 --> 00:21:15.700
cooking, eggs in
geothermal water.

00:21:15.700 --> 00:21:20.160
And again, that's an old
tradition that is not common

00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:22.830
anymore, but it is
something from the past

00:21:22.830 --> 00:21:25.835
that I think is really
fascinating and very uniquely

00:21:25.835 --> 00:21:26.335
Iceland.

00:21:28.766 --> 00:21:33.510
And so I just thought we could
talk a little bit about what

00:21:33.510 --> 00:21:39.140
Viking stock is, if
you can address that,

00:21:39.140 --> 00:21:42.920
and talk about why
Iceland's animals are

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:44.350
truly unique in the world?

00:21:45.250 --> 00:21:47.000
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
So it's like Iceland

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:53.680
has those rules somehow like
to protect their species.

00:21:54.920 --> 00:22:00.500
So it's illegal
to, for an example,

00:22:00.500 --> 00:22:04.102
if you were going to take this
horse to a show in Denmark,

00:22:04.102 --> 00:22:05.560
you're not allowed
to take it back.

00:22:06.590 --> 00:22:12.630
And you're not allowed to
import other types of horses.

00:22:12.630 --> 00:22:15.300
And this goes for, more
or less, every animal.

00:22:16.105 --> 00:22:17.480
JODY EDDY: And
these were animals

00:22:17.480 --> 00:22:20.900
that were introduced by the
Vikings in the 9th century.

00:22:20.900 --> 00:22:24.610
So they are unique species
on the planet because they

00:22:24.610 --> 00:22:26.435
have never bred
with other species.

00:22:27.230 --> 00:22:28.480
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Exactly.

00:22:28.480 --> 00:22:32.480
And it's is like-- maybe you
can speak about your goats?

00:22:37.400 --> 00:22:39.440
JODY EDDY: We met a
goat farmer in Iceland

00:22:39.440 --> 00:22:41.770
who had been a
nurse in Reykjavik.

00:22:41.770 --> 00:22:45.340
And she quit her job
maybe eight years ago

00:22:45.340 --> 00:22:47.660
because the Icelandic
goat population

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:50.730
had dipped to below 90 animals.

00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:54.010
And she realized that if
she didn't do something,

00:22:54.010 --> 00:22:55.300
they might go extinct.

00:22:55.300 --> 00:22:58.600
And so the goat
population now hovers

00:22:58.600 --> 00:23:00.470
around 900 animals in Iceland.

00:23:00.470 --> 00:23:05.630
And, truly, thanks to
Johanna Thorvaldsdottir,

00:23:05.630 --> 00:23:07.910
I think, because
of her work, people

00:23:07.910 --> 00:23:11.550
are starting to appreciate
the goats again and really see

00:23:11.550 --> 00:23:13.380
that it's important
to not only protect

00:23:13.380 --> 00:23:16.770
the goats for the sake of
the goats but it's a legacy

00:23:16.770 --> 00:23:19.280
and it's history that
they're protecting.

00:23:19.280 --> 00:23:23.890
But Johanna runs the
only commercial goat

00:23:23.890 --> 00:23:24.650
farm in Iceland.

00:23:24.650 --> 00:23:28.440
And she has about 400 of
the goats on her farm.

00:23:28.440 --> 00:23:31.830
And her farm was about to go
into foreclosure-- actually,

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:32.510
next week.

00:23:32.510 --> 00:23:36.600
And so they were going to
slaughter her goats, which

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:38.920
would mean it would wipe
out half the population.

00:23:38.920 --> 00:23:43.670
And so we started an
Indiegogo campaign for her,

00:23:43.670 --> 00:23:45.460
just me and a friend.

00:23:45.460 --> 00:23:50.600
And we've raised over
$110,000 in about a month.

00:23:50.600 --> 00:23:54.810
And her farm will be safe now,
and her goats will be saved.

00:23:54.810 --> 00:23:56.930
But I think the
important thing about it

00:23:56.930 --> 00:23:59.570
is that it really
speaks to the fact

00:23:59.570 --> 00:24:02.210
that the Icelandic
people are starting

00:24:02.210 --> 00:24:03.930
to appreciate what they have.

00:24:03.930 --> 00:24:07.170
And she has said to me,
since this campaign started,

00:24:07.170 --> 00:24:09.860
her tours on the farm have
increased exponentially

00:24:09.860 --> 00:24:12.800
because now there
is an appreciation.

00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:15.880
And I think it speaks to what
you're all about as well,

00:24:15.880 --> 00:24:19.000
that you have often used
ingredients that weren't

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:22.730
necessarily-- they weren't
used by Icelandic people,

00:24:22.730 --> 00:24:24.320
such as blue mussels.

00:24:24.320 --> 00:24:26.684
They have the most beautiful,
pristine blue muscles

00:24:26.684 --> 00:24:28.350
in Iceland, but they
weren't using them.

00:24:28.350 --> 00:24:30.820
And then when they
show up on your table,

00:24:30.820 --> 00:24:33.274
they start to show up on
other restaurant tables.

00:24:33.274 --> 00:24:35.190
And then maybe they're
bought by the consumer,

00:24:35.190 --> 00:24:37.990
and it's just interesting
to watch it trickle out.

00:24:38.295 --> 00:24:40.170
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Definately, definitely.

00:24:40.170 --> 00:24:44.660
And I mean like a lot of other
things, like for seaweed,

00:24:44.660 --> 00:24:45.960
for an example.

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:48.510
JODY EDDY: This
is actually-- he's

00:24:48.510 --> 00:24:51.170
the seaweed and blue
mussel harvester

00:24:51.170 --> 00:24:52.450
that Gunnar works with.

00:24:52.450 --> 00:24:55.350
Can you talk a little bit
more about him and his work?

00:24:56.760 --> 00:25:00.290
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Yeah, so his name is Simon.

00:25:00.290 --> 00:25:01.470
He lives in the west.

00:25:01.470 --> 00:25:03.400
He lives on the Snaefellsnes.

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:06.300
So he has a small company.

00:25:07.910 --> 00:25:10.980
I think there are like three
or something working there.

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:17.220
And so he grows blue
mussels and then

00:25:17.220 --> 00:25:20.880
he collects a couple
types of seaweed

00:25:20.880 --> 00:25:23.190
and sells to the
local restaurants.

00:25:23.190 --> 00:25:28.650
And he is even exporting
some of his seaweed as well.

00:25:28.650 --> 00:25:32.348
So he's doing great.

00:25:32.348 --> 00:25:35.631
JODY EDDY: Absolutely, so we'll
get to some of our producers

00:25:35.631 --> 00:25:36.130
here.

00:25:37.546 --> 00:25:40.925
So these are some of the herbs
that they use in Iceland.

00:25:40.925 --> 00:25:43.330
And what are some of
those common herbs

00:25:43.330 --> 00:25:45.580
that you'd find in
your kitchen at Dill?

00:25:45.580 --> 00:25:50.495
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Well, I
use probably most of angelica.

00:25:52.060 --> 00:25:56.140
Angelica, maybe chervil,
those are probably

00:25:56.140 --> 00:25:59.100
the most common ones
that I use a lot.

00:26:00.310 --> 00:26:04.540
Arctic thyme obviously,
really, really delicious,

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:06.910
especially when it's in bloom.

00:26:07.940 --> 00:26:10.140
But it's like, then
we take the trees,

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:13.280
we go for birch trees,
pine trees and et cetera.

00:26:14.480 --> 00:26:18.520
And probably like the best
part about foraging in Iceland

00:26:18.520 --> 00:26:23.890
is there are pretty much
nothing in the nature

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:26.760
that will actually kill
you if you taste it.

00:26:26.760 --> 00:26:29.070
So you can actually go,
you can just go there.

00:26:30.750 --> 00:26:34.087
You just go and taste
everything and you don't really

00:26:34.087 --> 00:26:35.045
have to worry about it.

00:26:35.045 --> 00:26:36.319
So that's pretty good.

00:26:36.319 --> 00:26:37.360
JODY EDDY: It's very fun.

00:26:37.360 --> 00:26:40.580
So Gunnar and I-- these are just
a few shots of Iceland itself.

00:26:40.580 --> 00:26:44.179
And we traveled, we probably
ringed the country--

00:26:44.179 --> 00:26:44.970
two or three times?

00:26:44.970 --> 00:26:46.080
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Yeah, probably.

00:26:46.080 --> 00:26:47.880
JODY EDDY: We hit every
corner of Iceland.

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:50.080
And it is very fun
to travel with him,

00:26:50.080 --> 00:26:52.770
because you do eat
everything and you

00:26:52.770 --> 00:26:55.100
learn so much about
what's around you.

00:26:55.100 --> 00:26:58.380
And I found myself, when I
travel in other countries,

00:26:58.380 --> 00:27:01.430
thinking about now
what I could try

00:27:01.430 --> 00:27:02.770
that I'm seeing on the ground.

