I wanted to try to talk a
lot about our producers,

00:27:49.320 --> 00:27:51.940
and especially
those that are doing

00:27:51.940 --> 00:27:56.845
their traditional stuff and
maybe kind of fading out.

00:27:56.845 --> 00:27:59.880
And I really wanted to have
a whole lot of landscape,

00:27:59.880 --> 00:28:01.750
because that somehow
it's like-- that's

00:28:01.750 --> 00:28:03.900
what inspires me, mostly.

00:28:05.150 --> 00:28:07.826
And then of course,
like the food.

00:28:07.826 --> 00:28:08.750
So it's-- yeah.

00:28:11.710 --> 00:28:15.560
JODY EDDY: This is bacalao,
which is salted cod.

00:28:15.560 --> 00:28:18.160
And can you talk a
little bit about Elvar,

00:28:18.160 --> 00:28:20.470
our bacalao producer
in the book.

00:28:20.470 --> 00:28:21.595
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:28:21.595 --> 00:28:24.530
So I've been buying
bacalao from Elvar

00:28:24.530 --> 00:28:27.720
for a lot of years,
many years actually.

00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:31.030
He lives in a really,
really small village

00:28:31.030 --> 00:28:34.075
in the North part of
Iceland called Hauganes.

00:28:34.075 --> 00:28:37.330
I think it's like 70 people
or something that lives there.

00:28:38.610 --> 00:28:41.020
And I think it's
like-- I think he said,

00:28:41.020 --> 00:28:43.860
I asked how many people
there from the village

00:28:43.860 --> 00:28:45.290
actually worked for him.

00:28:45.290 --> 00:28:48.820
I think he said all, except
two old ladies or something.

00:28:49.900 --> 00:28:51.770
JODY EDDY: He sustains
his entire village

00:28:51.770 --> 00:28:53.470
with his bacalao factory.

00:28:53.470 --> 00:28:55.261
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
He's a fantastic guy.

00:28:56.080 --> 00:29:04.170
So he's like third generation
of salted cod maker.

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:07.490
So what he has
there is obviously

00:29:07.490 --> 00:29:10.410
very important and dear to him.

00:29:11.560 --> 00:29:16.990
So he uses like
this old technique,

00:29:16.990 --> 00:29:23.080
so it takes up to a year
to make it, to salt it.

00:29:23.080 --> 00:29:25.630
And then they put it in
water actually, after.

00:29:26.870 --> 00:29:28.510
And he makes two kinds.

00:29:28.510 --> 00:29:31.350
He makes this one,
and then he makes

00:29:31.350 --> 00:29:36.090
one that is dried out
in the sun as well.

00:29:36.090 --> 00:29:39.970
And you can only imagine how
often that is in Iceland.

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:42.480
It's like it rains
constantly, so it's--

00:29:42.480 --> 00:29:43.690
JODY EDDY: It's a challenge.

00:29:43.690 --> 00:29:45.898
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah,
you have to jump out dry,

00:29:45.898 --> 00:29:48.680
and-- so it's a challenge.

00:29:48.680 --> 00:29:52.320
But as well, it's a lot
of fun to go and visit

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:53.500
him and talk to him.

00:29:57.372 --> 00:30:02.740
And get all his feelings
that he has for his company.

00:30:02.740 --> 00:30:06.310
And it makes it so much more
fun to actually use the product.

00:30:07.930 --> 00:30:12.550
And even to hear him say
like we've been asking him

00:30:12.550 --> 00:30:14.290
if he's pressing
his kids because--

00:30:15.370 --> 00:30:16.420
JODY EDDY: To take over.

00:30:16.420 --> 00:30:18.128
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Yeah, to take over,

00:30:18.128 --> 00:30:19.620
because they have
to be the fourth.

00:30:19.620 --> 00:30:21.120
JODY EDDY: He was
telling me that he

00:30:21.120 --> 00:30:24.760
might skip his daughters but
that his grandchildren are

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:26.190
very interested.

00:30:26.190 --> 00:30:29.260
But I think Elvar
really speaks to me

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:38.020
about-- if his work disappears,
he is maybe the last,

00:30:38.020 --> 00:30:40.909
if not one of the last
bacalao producers in Iceland.

00:30:40.909 --> 00:30:43.200
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: I think
there are probably three.

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:43.900
JODY EDDY: Yeah.

00:30:43.900 --> 00:30:46.410
And so he's a very
jovial person, one

00:30:46.410 --> 00:30:48.960
of the funniest people I've
ever met in Iceland or anywhere.

00:30:48.960 --> 00:30:50.830
But his work is important.

00:30:50.830 --> 00:30:52.390
It's really critical.

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:56.070
There was always that question
in the book to each producer,

00:30:56.070 --> 00:30:59.390
will somebody take over
this work do you think?

00:30:59.390 --> 00:31:02.044
With him there's optimism
there because his grandkids

00:31:02.044 --> 00:31:02.835
do seem interested.

00:31:03.958 --> 00:31:05.230
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:31:05.230 --> 00:31:05.834
Definitely.

00:31:05.834 --> 00:31:07.750
JODY EDDY: But it's been
interesting, as well,

00:31:07.750 --> 00:31:09.791
to meet with these producers
throughout the years

00:31:09.791 --> 00:31:12.130
because, you know, with
Elvar, he was really

00:31:12.130 --> 00:31:14.600
struggling after that
economic collapse.

00:31:14.600 --> 00:31:16.285
And I visited him.

00:31:16.285 --> 00:31:18.110
I do some Iceland
culinary tours,

00:31:18.110 --> 00:31:20.800
and I visited him
maybe last month.

00:31:20.800 --> 00:31:22.740
And he's doing better.

00:31:22.740 --> 00:31:26.200
He's selling to companies
throughout Europe.

00:31:27.510 --> 00:31:32.100
So it's been really great
to watch their evolution

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:35.750
and to see that they're
surviving and thriving

00:31:35.750 --> 00:31:37.250
in some cases.

00:31:37.250 --> 00:31:41.580
So this is the Arctic char
that you actually tried today.

00:31:43.330 --> 00:31:45.525
Can you talk a little bit
about him and his work?

00:31:45.525 --> 00:31:46.650
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:50.420
Those are the ones
that are smoking

00:31:50.420 --> 00:31:53.810
the old traditional way, the
one with the lamb manure.

00:31:55.070 --> 00:31:58.392
So his name is Gisli, and
he's married to my niece.

00:31:58.392 --> 00:31:59.220
JODY EDDY: Cousin.

00:31:59.220 --> 00:32:00.428
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Cousin.

00:32:00.928 --> 00:32:04.000
And they live in
[INAUDIBLE] which

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.450
is in the north part of
Iceland, actually not

00:32:06.450 --> 00:32:08.940
so far away from
where I actually come.

00:32:12.140 --> 00:32:14.580
I pretty much told you
all about that technique

00:32:14.580 --> 00:32:16.980
about that smoking.

00:32:16.980 --> 00:32:23.250
But it's actually a good story
as well because he actually

00:32:23.250 --> 00:32:26.465
smokes his fish like this so
it still has a lot of skin

00:32:26.465 --> 00:32:28.270
and a lot of bones on it.

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:31.100
He will then, after
smoking, he will cut off

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:34.130
the bones and all that stuff.

00:32:34.130 --> 00:32:36.220
And he actually
puts it in barrels

00:32:36.220 --> 00:32:39.500
and keeps the barrels outside
pretty much fermenting

00:32:39.500 --> 00:32:42.820
until the winter.

00:32:42.820 --> 00:32:45.640
And then he actually
gets the sheeps

00:32:45.640 --> 00:32:48.386
into the houses and he
actually feeds it to the--

00:32:48.386 --> 00:32:49.260
JODY EDDY: The bones.

00:32:49.260 --> 00:32:50.843
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
--to the sheeps.

00:32:51.530 --> 00:32:53.745
So it's like this
really nice circle

00:32:53.745 --> 00:32:55.620
because then they do
their thing on the floor

00:32:55.620 --> 00:32:58.370
and he uses it to smoke it.

00:32:58.370 --> 00:33:01.170
JODY EDDY: And these are
the geothermal bread ovens

00:33:01.170 --> 00:33:03.720
that you tasted the
geothermal bread today.

00:33:03.720 --> 00:33:07.580
And talk a little bit about
that and that tradition.

00:33:10.312 --> 00:33:12.270
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Especially in [INAUDIBLE]

00:33:12.270 --> 00:33:14.150
it's a big, big tradition.

00:33:15.940 --> 00:33:20.105
And each family usually
has their own hole.

00:33:20.105 --> 00:33:22.442
So it's like they just--

00:33:22.442 --> 00:33:24.650
JODY EDDY: That they inherit
through the generations.

00:33:24.650 --> 00:33:25.899
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Exactly.

00:33:25.899 --> 00:33:27.240
So they just continue using it.

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:29.030
And it's actually
quite interesting,

00:33:29.030 --> 00:33:32.020
you would think that they
would have to dig quite deep,

00:33:32.020 --> 00:33:33.730
but it's not deep at all.

00:33:33.730 --> 00:33:37.200
It's just like this
and the heat is there.

00:33:37.200 --> 00:33:41.240
JODY EDDY: They put their batter
in a bucket or sometimes a milk

00:33:41.240 --> 00:33:43.995
container and they leave it
for 24 hours and it cooks.

00:33:43.995 --> 00:33:45.245
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Exactly.

00:33:45.245 --> 00:33:45.745
Yeah.

00:33:45.745 --> 00:33:48.754
And usually it's baked in
those used milk containers

00:33:48.754 --> 00:33:49.420
for some reason.

00:33:50.805 --> 00:33:51.930
JODY EDDY: And there it is.

00:33:51.930 --> 00:33:53.720
They sometimes call
it geyser bread.

00:33:55.940 --> 00:33:59.450
And then this is a lamb
farmer that we met.

00:33:59.450 --> 00:34:01.820
And tell her story
and his story.

00:34:05.970 --> 00:34:08.739
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: I
actually used to work on a farm

00:34:08.739 --> 00:34:12.467
back in the days for his
grandmother and grandfather.

00:34:15.615 --> 00:34:19.260
So actually after his father and
mother stopped being farmers,

00:34:19.260 --> 00:34:21.250
he took over their farm.

00:34:21.250 --> 00:34:23.150
And that farm is
called Mother Daughter,

00:34:23.150 --> 00:34:29.060
and there's no farm in Iceland
that is on a higher level

00:34:29.060 --> 00:34:31.060
than their farm is.

00:34:32.380 --> 00:34:35.030
And it's actually
really impressive

00:34:35.030 --> 00:34:40.130
to come there and meet
them and especially

00:34:40.130 --> 00:34:44.250
see their sheeps actually,
because it's so high up

00:34:44.250 --> 00:34:46.550
and there's so little grass.

00:34:46.550 --> 00:34:49.049
So those sheeps, really
have to-- well, there's

00:34:49.049 --> 00:34:53.679
obviously a lot of grass
there-- but it's very, sandy.

00:34:53.679 --> 00:34:55.750
JODY EDDY: That's
a turf house, so--

00:34:55.750 --> 00:34:56.409
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
It's very sandy.

00:34:56.409 --> 00:34:58.033
So the sheeps, they
really have to work

00:34:58.033 --> 00:35:01.950
hard to find the right spots
and they do a lot of climbing.

00:35:01.950 --> 00:35:03.445
And they are massive.

00:35:03.445 --> 00:35:06.850
They are really,
really in good shape.

00:35:06.850 --> 00:35:10.805
JODY EDDY: And this is a
barley farmer in the east.

00:35:10.805 --> 00:35:12.590
He has a farm called Vallanes.

00:35:14.030 --> 00:35:18.770
Just quickly, Iceland
had prohibition on beer

00:35:18.770 --> 00:35:20.580
until, I think, the 1990s.

00:35:20.580 --> 00:35:24.577
And so they lost
their barley tradition

00:35:24.577 --> 00:35:26.660
because they weren't using
it for beer any longer.

00:35:26.660 --> 00:35:29.780
And he is really an
incredible person.

00:35:31.040 --> 00:35:33.660
I feel he maybe
single-handedly returned

00:35:33.660 --> 00:35:37.210
the tradition of using barley
to the Icelandic people.

00:35:38.295 --> 00:35:39.420
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:43.420
I think he's like one of very
few that actually grows barley.

00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:46.090
And it seems to go
very well for him.

00:35:46.090 --> 00:35:49.175
He as well makes a whole lot
of fantastic vegetables--

00:35:50.010 --> 00:35:51.510
JODY EDDY: That's
his barley fields.

00:35:51.510 --> 00:35:53.594
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
--that are organic and nice.

00:35:53.594 --> 00:35:54.093
Yeah.

00:35:54.093 --> 00:35:54.910
This is his barley.

00:35:54.910 --> 00:35:57.840
JODY EDDY: And he started
this farm in an area

00:35:57.840 --> 00:35:59.330
where there were no trees.

00:35:59.330 --> 00:36:02.660
And he said the
elevation is pretty high.

00:36:02.660 --> 00:36:05.360
And he said there was criticism
of him in the beginning

00:36:05.360 --> 00:36:07.680
because they said there's
not enough oxygen there

00:36:07.680 --> 00:36:08.860
to grow your barley.

00:36:08.860 --> 00:36:10.174
And he said, you know what?

00:36:10.174 --> 00:36:11.590
I'm going to create
my own oxygen.

00:36:11.590 --> 00:36:13.950
And he started his
farm 25 years ago

00:36:13.950 --> 00:36:17.620
and he's planted over a million
birch trees on his property.

00:36:17.620 --> 00:36:19.990
And he really has
created his own forest

00:36:19.990 --> 00:36:21.580
and his own ecosystem.

00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:23.210
He's incredibly inspiring.

00:36:23.210 --> 00:36:25.520
He has a company now
called Modir Jord

00:36:25.520 --> 00:36:28.300
that sells his barley
and other products.

00:36:28.300 --> 00:36:31.050
And you see it everywhere
in Iceland now.

00:36:31.050 --> 00:36:33.030
And, again, when I started
traveling in Iceland

00:36:33.030 --> 00:36:34.530
you couldn't find it anywhere.

00:36:34.530 --> 00:36:38.180
And it's encouraging
to see now that there's

00:36:38.180 --> 00:36:40.205
an interest in Iceland
for these products.

00:36:40.545 --> 00:36:41.670
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:36:41.670 --> 00:36:42.170
Definitely.

00:36:47.466 --> 00:36:53.490
When the crisis actually hit us,
which was obviously not really

00:36:53.490 --> 00:36:57.770
good, but there came a lot of
good things out of it, though.

00:36:57.770 --> 00:37:01.130
There seemed to be like a lot of
people that actually obviously

00:37:01.130 --> 00:37:05.350
lost their jobs, and they
would start thinking, OK, now I

00:37:05.350 --> 00:37:06.550
have to do something else.

00:37:07.570 --> 00:37:10.580
And there was no job to
get, so they pretty much had

00:37:10.580 --> 00:37:13.080
to find out something
new, something

00:37:13.080 --> 00:37:16.970
that they would like to do,
something that they obviously

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:17.810
knew.

00:37:17.810 --> 00:37:20.950
So they opened up like a
whole lot of new companies

00:37:20.950 --> 00:37:23.059
doing really, really
interesting things.

00:37:23.059 --> 00:37:24.600
JODY EDDY: And I
think as well, we've

00:37:24.600 --> 00:37:27.450
talked about how with
the economic crisis,

00:37:27.450 --> 00:37:30.300
beforehand everyone was
importing everything.

00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:34.317
And so they have this incredible
lamb, an amazing smoked lamb,

00:37:34.317 --> 00:37:36.400
but they were importing
prosciutto and eating that

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:37.106
instead.

00:37:37.106 --> 00:37:38.980
I mean, I think that's
a really good example.

00:37:38.980 --> 00:37:42.870
And after the crisis they could
no longer afford to do that.

00:37:42.870 --> 00:37:46.610
And so they started to
appreciate their smoked lamb,

00:37:46.610 --> 00:37:49.050
their other products that
were right around them

00:37:49.050 --> 00:37:50.392
at their feet.

00:37:50.392 --> 00:37:51.850
And it's certainly
a silver lining.

00:37:52.920 --> 00:37:53.990
You endured so much.

00:37:53.990 --> 00:37:54.490
But--

00:37:55.205 --> 00:37:56.330
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:37:56.330 --> 00:37:56.829
Definitely.

00:37:58.600 --> 00:38:01.850
JODY EDDY: Can you talk a little
bit about the dairy in Iceland?

00:38:01.850 --> 00:38:03.840
Icelanders consume
more dairy, I think,

00:38:03.840 --> 00:38:05.707
than any other
population in the world.

00:38:05.707 --> 00:38:07.290
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
I'm pretty sure.

00:38:07.290 --> 00:38:08.956
JODY EDDY: Talk a
little bit about skyr.

00:38:09.065 --> 00:38:10.190
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:38:10.190 --> 00:38:14.892
I think with the
dairies, I mean,

00:38:14.892 --> 00:38:16.850
there's not so much to
say about them, I guess.

00:38:16.850 --> 00:38:18.010
They are really good.

00:38:20.620 --> 00:38:24.230
But the biggest
tradition probably

00:38:24.230 --> 00:38:26.870
is an Icelandic milk
product called skyr.

00:38:28.130 --> 00:38:32.400
It's somewhere between a
yogurt and a cheese, actually.

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:36.920
And it's actually originally
it's made with live bacterias.

00:38:36.920 --> 00:38:41.100
So the farmers would usually
just skim their milk,

00:38:41.100 --> 00:38:43.130
so they would take
all the cream away.

00:38:43.130 --> 00:38:46.360
And they took the
fat free milk out.

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:50.600
And even the story says that
when they were moving or were

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:53.813
starting a farm somewhere,
they would split it

00:38:53.813 --> 00:38:55.860
in a couple of
jars-- take one down

00:38:55.860 --> 00:38:57.670
to the river, another
one to the sea,

00:38:57.670 --> 00:38:59.830
and one up to the
mountain or something

00:38:59.830 --> 00:39:01.383
so they could find
out where they

00:39:01.383 --> 00:39:04.140
could find the best starter.

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:07.850
So they would have
some live bacterias

00:39:07.850 --> 00:39:10.890
that they would sit down in
the milk and actually make it,

00:39:10.890 --> 00:39:12.305
what do you call it?

00:39:13.610 --> 00:39:14.484
Curdle, right?

00:39:14.484 --> 00:39:15.150
JODY EDDY: Yeah.

00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:18.180
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
And then they

00:39:18.180 --> 00:39:21.510
would get this product skyr,
and the other one called whey.

00:39:23.930 --> 00:39:29.290
That's like-- skyr is-- it's
like everybody in Iceland

00:39:29.290 --> 00:39:31.064
eats it at least
once a day, I think.

00:39:31.064 --> 00:39:31.980
JODY EDDY: Absolutely.

00:39:31.980 --> 00:39:32.600
GUNNAR KARL
GISLASON: It's crazy.

00:39:32.600 --> 00:39:33.766
JODY EDDY: And it's amazing.

00:39:34.265 --> 00:39:39.290
This is a birch forager
and producer that we met.

00:39:39.290 --> 00:39:43.529
And if you tasted Gunnar's
schnapps and liqueur,

00:39:43.529 --> 00:39:45.070
this is the forest
that it came from.

00:39:45.070 --> 00:39:47.760
And the birch twig inside
is from this forest.

00:39:48.860 --> 00:39:50.560
I think she's in
the east, as well.

00:39:50.560 --> 00:39:53.000
And she also
produces birch syrup,

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.300
which, again, I think was
a tradition that you used

00:39:55.300 --> 00:39:58.400
to have in Iceland and it
would decrease a little bit.

00:39:58.400 --> 00:40:02.210
And she now sells her birch
syrup throughout Iceland.

00:40:02.210 --> 00:40:04.260
And it seems to be
something that Icelanders

00:40:04.260 --> 00:40:04.969
are appreciating.

00:40:04.969 --> 00:40:06.260
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Oh, yeah.

00:40:06.260 --> 00:40:06.780
Definitely.

00:40:06.780 --> 00:40:12.320
And she makes a lot of spice
blends and salts and et cetera,

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:15.592
all just using the
birch three, actually.

00:40:17.008 --> 00:40:18.690
JODY EDDY: And there's
one of his sous

00:40:18.690 --> 00:40:20.000
chefs with his birch tattoo.

00:40:20.965 --> 00:40:22.090
That's how important it is.

00:40:23.350 --> 00:40:27.670
This is the salt maker from
Saltverk, the geothermal salt

00:40:27.670 --> 00:40:29.620
company that we covered.

00:40:29.620 --> 00:40:32.090
And I think that story's
very interesting.

00:40:32.090 --> 00:40:34.275
And tell a little bit more
about how that started.

00:40:34.275 --> 00:40:35.650
GUNNAR KARL
GISLASON: Definitely.

00:40:35.650 --> 00:40:38.520
Well it started
actually in Denmark.

00:40:38.520 --> 00:40:40.640
So there were like
two friends that

00:40:40.640 --> 00:40:42.915
went to Denmark to
study to be engineers.

00:40:44.490 --> 00:40:46.560
For some reason that
I can't remember,

00:40:46.560 --> 00:40:50.490
they started reading some
books, like old books.

00:40:50.490 --> 00:40:53.210
And then they found out that
the Danish king actually

00:40:53.210 --> 00:40:55.600
had people making salt
in Iceland for him

00:40:55.600 --> 00:40:57.020
back in the days.

00:40:57.020 --> 00:41:01.390
So they started to
take a look into that

00:41:01.390 --> 00:41:04.552
and actually ended up opening
up their own salt company.

00:41:04.552 --> 00:41:06.260
JODY EDDY: And they're
doing really well.

00:41:07.740 --> 00:41:09.307
And that, again,
when we started,

00:41:09.307 --> 00:41:11.140
you really couldn't
find their salt anywhere

00:41:11.140 --> 00:41:12.290
and now it's everywhere.

00:41:12.290 --> 00:41:15.510
Every restaurant table
that I saw last month

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:17.512
seemed to have
Saltverk on the table.

00:41:17.512 --> 00:41:18.220
It's encouraging.

00:41:18.220 --> 00:41:18.823
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
The thing as well

00:41:18.823 --> 00:41:20.073
is that it's like for Iceland.

00:41:20.073 --> 00:41:22.090
And in Iceland, at
the end of the day,

00:41:22.090 --> 00:41:24.440
it's like we're only
like 320,000 people.

00:41:24.440 --> 00:41:26.040
So it's like, if
you will come up

00:41:26.040 --> 00:41:28.230
with a product that is
actually really good,

00:41:28.230 --> 00:41:32.800
it's actually kind of easy
to-- what do you call it?

00:41:34.439 --> 00:41:35.480
JODY EDDY: Distribute it?

00:41:35.480 --> 00:41:37.896
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Get it
to the market, yeah, exactly.

00:41:38.820 --> 00:41:40.964
People will talk about it.

00:41:40.964 --> 00:41:41.630
JODY EDDY: Yeah.

00:41:41.630 --> 00:41:43.796
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Like
one restaurant to another

00:41:43.796 --> 00:41:45.600
or one house mother to another.

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:48.114
People will talk and
it will go really fast.

00:41:48.114 --> 00:41:50.030
But at the same time,
it's like if you come up

00:41:50.030 --> 00:41:52.290
with something horrible
it's never going to work.

00:41:52.290 --> 00:41:54.581
JODY EDDY: Because everyone's
going to talk about that.

00:41:55.320 --> 00:41:57.710
And this is hardfiskur
that you tried today.

00:42:01.890 --> 00:42:06.980
So, again, what I
think is inspiring

00:42:06.980 --> 00:42:08.680
as well in Iceland
is they really try,

00:42:08.680 --> 00:42:10.500
I think, to use
all their products.

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:12.460
So these are drying racks.

00:42:12.460 --> 00:42:15.850
They use only the fillets
of the wolffish fish

00:42:15.850 --> 00:42:18.440
for the hardfiskur,
but they then

00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:20.620
dry the heads and the
bones and they send them

00:42:20.620 --> 00:42:23.540
to parts of Africa where
they're used in stews.

00:42:23.540 --> 00:42:24.665
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:42:24.665 --> 00:42:25.164
Exactly.

00:42:28.474 --> 00:42:30.140
A lot of those
companies, and especially

00:42:30.140 --> 00:42:31.639
the companies in
fish, they will try

00:42:31.639 --> 00:42:35.880
to use every single
part of the fish.

00:42:35.880 --> 00:42:38.010
And it's the same as
like with the restaurant.

00:42:38.010 --> 00:42:41.260
It's something that we focus
really, really hard on.

00:42:43.270 --> 00:42:47.800
We want to get whole pieces
of whatever we are buying

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:50.510
and we want to use
every single part of it.

00:42:53.130 --> 00:42:55.800
Or even if we are not
going to buy whole things,

00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:58.860
we will buy some strange part
that nobody else is using.

00:42:59.890 --> 00:43:02.800
As well, it's like
with everything--

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:04.290
like with vegetables,
for example--

00:43:04.290 --> 00:43:09.690
it's like we try to use
if it comes with roots

00:43:09.690 --> 00:43:12.290
and it comes with the
leaves, we will use it all.

00:43:12.290 --> 00:43:20.560
And unfortunately, so many
farmers and people in general,

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:22.310
they don't know
what-- like, they

00:43:22.310 --> 00:43:25.620
will get a celeriac
or something.

00:43:25.620 --> 00:43:27.850
And they will get it
so they have already

00:43:27.850 --> 00:43:30.290
cut the roots and
the leaves off,

00:43:30.290 --> 00:43:34.530
which is a shame because it's
really, really good, as well.

00:43:34.530 --> 00:43:37.090
So we try to talk
about those things

00:43:37.090 --> 00:43:40.850
and get people to bring the
whole thing so we can just

00:43:40.850 --> 00:43:41.350
use it.

00:43:41.350 --> 00:43:43.160
We even have our
farmers bringing us

00:43:43.160 --> 00:43:46.240
the wheat that grows
around the vegetables

00:43:46.240 --> 00:43:49.020
because we will use
that for salad, as well.

00:43:49.020 --> 00:43:52.880
Everything from like
the peel from the onions

00:43:52.880 --> 00:43:57.291
we will put on a hot plate
in summer until it's dry,

00:43:57.291 --> 00:43:58.790
and then we'll use
it to smoke with.

00:44:01.060 --> 00:44:04.360
So we try to question
every single piece that

00:44:04.360 --> 00:44:08.570
goes into the truss and
ask, what can I do with it?

00:44:08.570 --> 00:44:11.070
JODY EDDY: I think this is
the blue mussel producer

00:44:11.070 --> 00:44:13.770
that Gunnar works with.

00:44:13.770 --> 00:44:15.600
And he has told
this story about how

00:44:15.600 --> 00:44:18.750
when Gunnar started
placing his mussel orders,

00:44:18.750 --> 00:44:21.030
they were the only
orders coming in.

00:44:21.030 --> 00:44:23.840
And he would go out to
sea to collect sometimes

00:44:23.840 --> 00:44:25.790
2 kilos for you and that was it.

00:44:25.790 --> 00:44:28.190
And now he really is
having a hard time,

00:44:28.190 --> 00:44:31.216
I think, keeping up with
business and the demand.

00:44:31.216 --> 00:44:32.340
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:44:32.340 --> 00:44:33.450
I think it's going good.

00:44:33.450 --> 00:44:34.908
JODY EDDY: But I
think it certainly

00:44:34.908 --> 00:44:37.560
speaks to you just
really putting

00:44:37.560 --> 00:44:41.070
that on the table at Dill and
allowing people to experience

00:44:41.070 --> 00:44:43.800
it and then to want it
everywhere they go in Iceland.

00:44:43.800 --> 00:44:45.120
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:44:45.120 --> 00:44:50.570
And for me it's really fun
to keep this good connection

00:44:50.570 --> 00:44:57.040
to those guys and being able
to know what is behind it

00:44:57.040 --> 00:45:01.600
and what they have been
doing or sacrificing

00:45:01.600 --> 00:45:03.700
to bring those products to me.

00:45:04.954 --> 00:45:05.830
JODY EDDY: Yeah.

00:45:05.830 --> 00:45:06.330
Absolutely.

00:45:06.330 --> 00:45:08.575
And this is our sea
bird egg collector.

00:45:08.575 --> 00:45:09.700
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:45:09.700 --> 00:45:11.650
So this is out in Grimsey.

00:45:11.650 --> 00:45:13.900
It's actually the
northest part of Iceland.

00:45:15.080 --> 00:45:18.420
It's a three hour
trip on a ship.

00:45:18.420 --> 00:45:21.125
JODY EDDY: It's an island
on the Arctic Circle.

00:45:21.125 --> 00:45:22.250
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:45:22.250 --> 00:45:22.900
It's a very small island.

00:45:22.900 --> 00:45:23.399
Yeah.

00:45:23.399 --> 00:45:25.750
The Arctic Circle goes
through it, literally.

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:31.100
And my friend, Sigi, he actually
goes on a rope down those

00:45:31.100 --> 00:45:33.190
cliffs to collect those eggs.

00:45:33.190 --> 00:45:34.900
JODY EDDY: There's
some pictures of him.

00:45:34.900 --> 00:45:35.950
It's really intense.

00:45:37.751 --> 00:45:39.000
And they're not attached, too.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:43.530
In contemporary climbing, you
attach yourself to the ground,

00:45:43.530 --> 00:45:47.320
but his rope was wrapped
around a tractor hitch

00:45:47.320 --> 00:45:50.190
that Gunnar was holding,
and that was it.

00:45:50.190 --> 00:45:53.820
And we asked him if
there are ever accidents

00:45:53.820 --> 00:45:55.265
and he said, yeah, all the time.

00:45:56.560 --> 00:45:58.220
But he continues to do his work.

00:45:58.220 --> 00:46:01.280
And it's inspiring, but
a little disconcerting

00:46:01.280 --> 00:46:04.320
too, what he's doing
to collect those eggs.

00:46:04.320 --> 00:46:06.360
But I think certainly,
again, it speaks

00:46:06.360 --> 00:46:08.690
to the perseverance
and the determination

00:46:08.690 --> 00:46:11.600
to keep tradition alive
amongst some people.

00:46:11.600 --> 00:46:15.230
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
And it's funny,

00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:18.770
he would go and collect them
and then he just has a lot.

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:20.440
And the other people
from the island,

00:46:20.440 --> 00:46:21.990
they will know that
he went yesterday

00:46:21.990 --> 00:46:23.880
and then they'll come
and get a couple of eggs.

00:46:23.880 --> 00:46:25.690
JODY EDDY: They have kind
of a collecting area, right?

00:46:25.690 --> 00:46:26.240
A cooler.

00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:29.230
There's 86 people on
the island, so it's

00:46:29.230 --> 00:46:30.546
a small, tight-knit community.

00:46:30.546 --> 00:46:32.670
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: A
very, very small community.

00:46:32.670 --> 00:46:34.378
JODY EDDY: The eggs
are shaped like cones

00:46:34.378 --> 00:46:36.800
because the birds
don't build nests.

00:46:36.800 --> 00:46:39.105
And so they just have
evolved into cones

00:46:39.105 --> 00:46:40.980
so they don't roll off
the side of the cliff.

00:46:41.921 --> 00:46:42.545
Very practical.

00:46:43.720 --> 00:46:47.780
And we had some fantastic
hard boiled sea bird eggs

00:46:47.780 --> 00:46:48.310
that night.

00:46:54.450 --> 00:46:56.870
Sigi is also a
fisherman and so we

00:46:56.870 --> 00:47:00.410
went out with him about 40
kilometers into the ocean

00:47:00.410 --> 00:47:01.400
and fished.

00:47:01.400 --> 00:47:04.940
And he, as well, talked
about the challenges

00:47:04.940 --> 00:47:06.985
with the fishing quotas now.

00:47:06.985 --> 00:47:09.750
The government can
be-- it's a struggle.

00:47:09.750 --> 00:47:12.290
And he's actually gone north.

00:47:12.290 --> 00:47:14.580
His family is not
from the island.

00:47:14.580 --> 00:47:16.440
They used to fish in
the southern parts,

00:47:16.440 --> 00:47:20.130
but because the fish are moving
further north because probably

00:47:20.130 --> 00:47:24.099
from global warming, he's had to
move north to follow the fish.

00:47:24.099 --> 00:47:25.640
But he's on the top
of the world now.

00:47:25.640 --> 00:47:28.360
So you have to wonder what
he's going to do next.

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:30.526
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: He's
not going any more north.

00:47:31.830 --> 00:47:35.960
JODY EDDY: And this is some of
the goat sausage from the goat

00:47:35.960 --> 00:47:38.304
farmer that we mentioned before.

00:47:38.304 --> 00:47:39.720
And those are her
Icelandic goats.

00:47:42.450 --> 00:47:43.650
There's Gunnar.

00:47:43.650 --> 00:47:45.780
We spent a lot of time
with those goats one day.

00:47:45.780 --> 00:47:45.900
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:47:45.900 --> 00:47:46.775
That was pretty neat.

00:47:47.195 --> 00:47:48.320
JODY EDDY: There's Johanna.

00:47:52.500 --> 00:47:56.270
And these are the lava fields on
the way to the hakarl producer.

00:47:56.270 --> 00:47:57.485
He's the shark maker.

00:47:59.930 --> 00:48:02.610
And there's his putrefied shark.

00:48:04.170 --> 00:48:05.460
He eats his shark--

00:48:05.460 --> 00:48:06.660
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
It tastes like cheese.

00:48:06.660 --> 00:48:09.201
JODY EDDY: It supposedly tastes
like a really strong Stilton.

00:48:09.779 --> 00:48:10.320
I don't know.

00:48:10.320 --> 00:48:12.450
I've had it a few
times and I could never

00:48:12.450 --> 00:48:13.500
discover that flavor.

00:48:15.580 --> 00:48:18.160
He eats a shark sandwich
every day, this producer.

00:48:19.250 --> 00:48:20.260
And he swears by it.

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:22.180
And he's 80 and his
skin is fantastic.

00:48:23.520 --> 00:48:25.530
I think there's something
to the shark oil.

00:48:25.530 --> 00:48:28.075
And he's so enthusiastic
about his work.

00:48:31.360 --> 00:48:33.220
And there's the
shark fermenting.

00:48:34.492 --> 00:48:35.950
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
They actually

00:48:35.950 --> 00:48:40.370
start with like fermenting
the sharks in those barrels

00:48:40.370 --> 00:48:43.820
under like a pressure before
they actually then hang them up

00:48:43.820 --> 00:48:44.750
to dry.

00:48:47.330 --> 00:48:50.880
JODY EDDY: Here's some
pictures from our photo shoots.

00:48:50.880 --> 00:48:53.240
It was really challenging
to shoot outside.

00:48:54.470 --> 00:48:56.530
So we didn't do all
of our shoots inside.

00:48:57.580 --> 00:48:59.165
With Icelandic weather--

00:48:59.165 --> 00:49:00.510
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: So
if you're doing a book

00:49:00.510 --> 00:49:01.910
and the photographer
says that he

00:49:01.910 --> 00:49:04.600
wants to use the natural light
because it's so beautiful,

00:49:04.600 --> 00:49:05.500
don't listen to him.

00:49:05.500 --> 00:49:07.340
JODY EDDY: Just say no.

00:49:07.340 --> 00:49:12.380
In a rainstorm all his mise en
place strewn across the stones.

00:49:12.380 --> 00:49:13.970
It was a challenge.

00:49:13.970 --> 00:49:17.560
And there's Gunnar's-- I love
this picture-- your daughter,

00:49:17.560 --> 00:49:20.437
who is contemplating
one of your dishes.

00:49:20.437 --> 00:49:22.020
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
Checking it out.

00:49:22.020 --> 00:49:23.080
JODY EDDY: Yeah.

00:49:23.080 --> 00:49:23.580
Absolutely.

00:49:23.580 --> 00:49:27.590
And for the book Gunnar's
friend, August, took us out

00:49:27.590 --> 00:49:31.020
in his prop plane and we
did some aerial shots.

00:49:32.397 --> 00:49:33.480
I was sitting in the back.

00:49:33.480 --> 00:49:35.450
It was a little
nerve-racking every time

00:49:35.450 --> 00:49:37.450
he would open up the
window and they would shoot

00:49:37.450 --> 00:49:39.310
and then he would
tip to the side right

00:49:39.310 --> 00:49:41.910
over the volcano
that had exploded

00:49:41.910 --> 00:49:45.677
in 2011 or over
a glacier, but we

00:49:45.677 --> 00:49:47.260
did what we had to
do to get the shot.

00:49:49.700 --> 00:49:51.740
It was really fascinating
to see Iceland

00:49:51.740 --> 00:49:53.260
after all these
years from the air

00:49:53.260 --> 00:49:54.593
and see how it all fit together.

00:49:58.655 --> 00:50:02.080
I have a picture here of coffee.

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:05.000
I think it really speaks
to where Iceland is at now

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:07.440
and how it's evolved
since the crisis.

00:50:07.440 --> 00:50:10.970
This is a friend of Gunnar's
who runs this company.

00:50:10.970 --> 00:50:16.150
And I think just the care that's
going into his product I think

00:50:16.150 --> 00:50:20.860
speaks to a lot of the care and
diligence that a lot of people

00:50:20.860 --> 00:50:25.720
have now to creating artisanal
beers and products that really

00:50:25.720 --> 00:50:28.780
are of high quality and using
Icelandic-- coffee isn't

00:50:28.780 --> 00:50:33.820
an Icelandic ingredient, but
in terms of just focusing on

00:50:33.820 --> 00:50:34.855
of making it the best.

00:50:35.305 --> 00:50:36.430
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: Yeah.

00:50:36.430 --> 00:50:39.650
Actually if you're
importing it, then you

00:50:39.650 --> 00:50:41.134
should import something good.

00:50:41.134 --> 00:50:41.800
JODY EDDY: Yeah.

00:50:41.800 --> 00:50:42.460
Absolutely.

00:50:42.460 --> 00:50:45.260
To talk a little bit about
the serviceware in the book,

00:50:45.260 --> 00:50:48.320
everything was sourced
from Icelandic potters.

00:50:48.320 --> 00:50:51.110
And we even had some of
the service wear brought

00:50:51.110 --> 00:50:53.939
from the National Art Museum
that he was shooting on,

00:50:53.939 --> 00:50:56.230
and then we had to run it
back to the museum that night

00:50:56.230 --> 00:50:57.400
because they were not happy.

00:50:59.020 --> 00:51:04.010
But even some of the pelts that
are used in the background,

00:51:04.010 --> 00:51:08.335
we had a seal pelt and reindeer
hides and it's very inspiring.

00:51:11.500 --> 00:51:14.890
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON:
And it's all right now

00:51:14.890 --> 00:51:16.662
everything at the restaurant.

00:51:16.662 --> 00:51:17.995
So those pictures are actually--

00:51:19.270 --> 00:51:21.980
JODY EDDY: Those are my
photos that I took at dinner.

00:51:21.980 --> 00:51:24.940
GUNNAR KARL GISLASON: They
are from our ex-location.

00:51:24.940 --> 00:51:28.690
So we just moved
like four months ago.

00:51:28.690 --> 00:51:32.150
And if I was moving
anyway, we decided

00:51:32.150 --> 00:51:36.330
to take the whole
thing even further,

00:51:36.330 --> 00:51:38.820
make it even more Icelandic.

00:51:38.820 --> 00:51:41.660
So now everything
in the restaurant--

00:51:41.660 --> 00:51:45.830
like the chairs, the
tables, every plate,

00:51:45.830 --> 00:51:49.210
and all this stuff, everything
is handcrafted in Iceland.

00:51:51.480 --> 00:51:55.230
We have some lamb
leather on the chairs.

00:51:55.230 --> 00:51:58.350
And it's really, really, really
pretty and it's very Icelandic.

00:52:00.370 --> 00:52:01.330
And I'm very happy.

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:04.110
JODY EDDY: Very
much you, I think.

00:52:04.110 --> 00:52:05.486
GUNNAR KARL
GISLASON: Definitely.

00:52:05.486 --> 00:52:07.526
JODY EDDY: So there's our
photographer and Gunnar

00:52:07.526 --> 00:52:08.050
on the road.

00:52:08.050 --> 00:52:09.405
Does anybody have any questions?

00:52:09.957 --> 00:52:12.040
AUDIENCE: You've obviously
done a really great job

00:52:12.040 --> 00:52:13.840
of telling the story
of the producers

00:52:13.840 --> 00:52:16.860
and the origins of the
ingredients and everything.

00:52:16.860 --> 00:52:19.960
Is that a responsibility
that more chefs should do?

00:52:19.960 --> 00:52:23.500
Is it something that needs to
be done in more restaurants?

00:52:23.500 --> 00:52:26.810
And if so, how best to
do it to a dining crowd

00:52:26.810 --> 00:52:29.920
that's here to eat
their meal and then they

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:31.090
leave to do something else.

00:52:31.090 --> 00:52:33.175
How do you balance
the story that you've

00:52:33.175 --> 00:52:35.300
told in the book with the
guests in the restaurant?

